<Project slug="infosec-policy-library">
  <p class="lead">
    Policies are the documented expression of an information security programme.
    Most candidates can describe what policies an ISMS needs; very few have
    written one that would survive an ISO 27001 audit.
  </p>

  <h2>The problem I wanted to solve</h2>
  <p>
    A gap analysis tells you whether a policy is missing or not. A risk register tells you what
    the absence could cost. But neither closes the gap that takes the actual
    documented standard. I wanted to produce a complete policy library that
    demonstrates my capability to write governance documents in the voice and structure
    which CISOs and auditors recognise: specific and enforceable, not aspirational.
  </p>

  <h2>How I approached it</h2>

  <h3>Building the register first</h3>
  <p>
    Before writing a single policy I built the policy register — the governance
    structure that everything else hangs off. It establishes what gets tracked,
    who owns each policy, how reviews are scheduled and how exceptions are
    managed. Six sheets cover the cover page, a dashboard, the policy register
    itself, a compliance mapping, the review schedule and an exceptions tracker.
    A library without this scaffolding is just a folder of documents; with it,
    it's a managed control.
  </p>

  <h3>One 10-section template, applied seven times</h3>
  <p>
    Then I wrote seven policies as individual standalone documents — the way real
    organisations maintain them, not bound together in one binder. Every policy
    follows the same 10-section template, so they read as one coherent library:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Document Control · Purpose · Scope · Definitions</li>
    <li>Roles &amp; Responsibilities (RACI-style)</li>
    <li>Policy Statements — the substantive, enforceable section</li>
    <li>Exceptions · Compliance &amp; Enforcement</li>
    <li>Related Documents · Review &amp; Maintenance · Document History</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Statements that are enforceable, not aspirational</h3>
  <div class="callout">
    <span class="section-mark">The difference that matters</span>
    <p>
      The policy statements are specific and testable. "Multi-Factor
      Authentication is mandatory for all users" — not "appropriate authentication
      should be considered". An auditor can verify the first; the second is a
      wish. Mandatory requirements use <strong>shall</strong>, grouped under
      numbered subsection headings.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Anchoring to specific regulations</h3>
  <p>
    Each policy's Related Documents section cites the exact ISO 27001 Annex A
    controls, MAS TRM sections and PDPA / PCI DSS requirements that it operationalizes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-001 Acceptable Use </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.5.10–A.6</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 3.2/3.5</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 12.3</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-002 Access Control </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.5.15–A.8.5</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 9.1/9.2</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 7,8</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-003 Data Classification </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.5.12–A.8.12</span> <span class="cite">PDPA 11–26</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 3</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-004 Incident Response </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.5.24–A.5.30</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 7.5</span> <span class="cite">PDPA 26A–D</span> <span class="cite">NIST SP 800-61</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-005 Remote Working </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.6.7/A.7.9/A.8.1</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 9.1.6</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 8.3</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-006 Cryptography </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.8.24</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 9.4</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 3,4</span> <span class="cite">NIST FIPS 140-3</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>POL-007 Secure SDLC </strong>
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.8.25–A.8.31</span> <span class="cite">MAS TRM 6</span> <span class="cite">PCI DSS 6</span> <span class="cite">OWASP ASVS/SAMM</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Depth beyond the obvious</h3>
  <p>
    The two optional policies, Cryptography (POL-006) and Secure SDLC (POL-007) are included to demonstrate depth in technical security domains
    and not just governance paperwork. A payments fintech company under PCI DSS will need both.
  </p>

  <h2>What I produced</h2>
  <p>
    A six-sheet Excel policy register (register, compliance mapping, review
    schedule, exceptions tracker, dashboard and cover) plus seven standalone
    policy documents in Word; each roughly six to eight pages, all built on the
    same 10-section template. Together: a comprehensive policy library with the
    governance tracking that keeps it currently aligned.
  </p>

  <h2>What this demonstrates</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>I can author governance documents that read as operational, not aspirational.</li>
    <li>I understand how policies fit into an ISMS; the register tracks them, the exceptions process governs them, the review schedule keeps them current.</li>
    <li>I apply Singapore regulatory context to each policy domain with specific citations.</li>
    <li>The two technical policies show depth beyond pure governance writing.</li>
  </ul>
</Project>
